name: Building
comments: A category that includes devices as described by building related data models, such as IFC and FIEMSER
definitions: A category that includes devices as described by building related data models, such as IFC and FIEMSER

name: Room
comments: A room in a building. This class may be used to group devices.

name: Tenant
comments: A class that describes information about a tenant in a building.

name: Command
comments: A directive that a device must support to perform a certain function. A command may act upon a state, but does not necessarily act upon a state. For example, the ON command acts upon the ON/OFF state, but the GET command does not act upon any state, it simply gives a directive to retrieve a certain value. We propose here a list of commands that are relevant for the purpose of SAREF, but this list can be extended.

name: Close command
comments: A type of command

name: Get Current Meter Value Command
comments: A type of get command

name: Get meter data command
comments: A type of get command

name: Get meter history command
comments: A type of get command

name: Get sensing data command
comments: A type of get command

name: Commodity
comments: A marketable item for which there is demand, but which is supplied without qualitative differentiation across a market. SAREF refers to energy commodities such as electricity, gas, coal and oil.

name: Device
comments: A tangible object designed to accomplish a particular task in households, common public buildings or offices. In order to accomplish this task, the device performs one or more functions. For example, a washing machine is designed to wash (task) and to accomplish this task it performs a start and stop function. Devices can be structured in categories (subclasses) that reflect the different domain in which a device is used, e.g., smart appliances domain (subclass FunctionRelated) vs. building domain (subclass BuildingRelated) vs. smart grid domain (subclass EnergyRelated). New categories can be defined,if needed, to reflect other differences, for example different points of view, such as the point of view of the device's user vs. the point of view of the device's manufacturer. We propose a list of devices that are relevant for the purpose of SAREF, but this list can be extended.

name: Building related
comments: A building represents a structure that provides shelter for its occupants or contents and stands in one place. The building is also used to provide a basic element within the spatial structure hierarchy for the components of a building project (together with site, storey, and space).

name: Actuator
comments: A device responsible for moving or controlling a mechanism or system by performing an actuating function

name: Switch
comments: A device of category saref:Actuator that performs an actuating function of type saref:OnOffFunction or saref:OpenCloseFunction

name: Door switch
comments: A device of category saref:Actuator that consists of a switch, accomplishes the task saref:Safety, performs the saref:OpenCloseFunction, is used for controlling a door, and can be found in the state saref:OpenCloseState.

name: Switch
comments: A device of category saref:Actuator that consists of a switch, accomplishes the task saref:Lighting, performs the saref:OnOffFunction, measures the property saref:Light, and can be found in the state saref:OnOffState. It can offer a switch on service.

name: Controller
comments: A device that detects and responds to events or changes in the physical environment such as light, motion, or temperature changes. Further, a device of category saref:Sensor that performs a saref:SensingFunction.

name: SmokeSensor
comments: A device that consists of a sensor, has category saref:Sensor, performs the saref:SensingFunction and saref:EventFunction (which notifies that a certain threshold has been exceeded), and is used for the purpose of sensing a property of type saref:Smoke.

name: TemperatureSensor
comments: A device that consists of a sensor, has category saref:Sensor, performs the saref:SensingFunction and is used for the purpose of sensing a property of type saref:Temperature

name: Grid Related
comments: A category that considers devices based on energy consumption information and profiles to optimize energy efficiency.

name: Lighting device
comments: A device used for illumination, irradiation, signaling, or projection

name: Washing machine
comments: A device of category saref:Appliance and saref:Load that accomplishes the task saref:Washing, performs an actuating function of type saref:StartStopFunction, can be found in the state saref:StartStopState, and can have a saref:Profile that characterizes its energy consumption.

name: Meter
comments: A device built to accurately detect and display a quantity in a form readable by a human being. Further, a device of category saref:Meter that performs a saref:MeteringFunction.

name: Energy Meter
comments: An energy meter is a device of category saref:Meter that consists of a meter, accomplishes the tasks saref:MeterReading and saref:EnergyEfficiency, performs the saref:MeteringFunction and is used for the purpose of measuring the saref:Energy property.

name: Micro renewable
comments: A device that generates renewable energy from natural resources such as teh sun, wind and water

name: Storage
comments: A type of energy-related device that stores energy

name: Function
comments: The functionality necessary to accomplish the task for which a Device is designed. A device can be designed to perform more than one function. Functions can be structured in categories (subclasses) that reflect different points of view, for example, considering the specific application area for which a function can be used (e.g., light, temperature, motion, heat, power, etc.), or the capability that a function can support (e.g., receive, reply, notify, etc.), and so forth.

name: Actuating Function
comments: A function that allows to transmit data to actuators, such as level settings (e.g., temperature) or binary switching (e.g., open/close, on/off)

name: Actuating Function
comments: An actuating function that allows to do level adjustments of an actuator in a certain range (e.g., 0%-100%), such as dimming a light or set the speed of an electric motor.

name: On off Function
comments: An actuating function that allows to switch on and off an actuator.

name: Open close Function
comments: An actuating function that allows to open and close a device.

name: Start stop function
comments: An actuating function that allows to start and stop a device.

name: Event Function
comments: A function that allows to notify another device that a certain threshold value has been exceeded.

name: Metering Function
comments: A function that allows to get data from a meter, such as current meter reading or instantaneous demand.

name: Sensing Function
comments: A function that allows to transmit data from sensors, such as measurement values (e.g., temperature) or sensing data (e.g., occupancy).

name: Measurement
comments: Represents the measured value made over a property. It is also linked to the unit of measure in which the value is expressed and the timestamp of the measurement.

name: Currency unit
comments: The unit of measure for price.

name: Energy unit
comments: The unit of measure for energy.

name: Power unit
comments: The unit of measure for power.

name: Pressure unit
comments: The unit of measure for pressure.

name: Temperature_unit
comments: The unit of measure for temperature.

name: Profile
comments: A specification associated to a device to collect information about a certain Property (e.g., Energy) or Commodity (e.g.Water) for optimizing its usage in the home, office or building in which the device is located. This specification is about a certain Property or Commodity (saref:isAbout), can be calculated over a time span (saref:hasTime ) and can be associated to some costs (saref:hasPrice). An example is the Power Profile defined in the SAREF4ENER extension that can be associated to a device for optimizing the Energy efficiency in the home, office or building in which the device is located.

name: Property
comments: Anything that can be sensed, measured or controlled in households, common public buildings or offices. We propose here a list of properties that are relevant for the purpose of SAREF, but this list can be extended.

name: CO2_level
comments: A property related to measurements of CO2 level in the air. Measured in ppm.

name: Current
comments: A property related to measurements measured in Ampere (A).

name: Flow
comments: A property related to measurements of rates of flow, measured in m³/s. This may for instance be used to measure air flow in ventilation or water flow in district heating systems.

name: Humidity
comments: A saref:Property related to some measurements that are characterized by a certain value that is measured in a humidity unit.

name: Light
comments: A saref:Property related to some measurements that are characterized by a certain value that is measured in a illuminance unit (lux).

name: Motion
comments: A saref:Property related to some measurements that are characterized by a certain value that is measured in a unit of measure for motion.

name: Occupancy
comments: A saref:Property related to some measurements that are characterized by a certain value (saref:hasValue property) that is measured in a unit of measure for occupancy.

name: Power
comments: A saref:Property related to some measurements that are characterized by a certain value that is measured in a power unit (such as watt or kilowatt).  Further specializations of the saref:Power class can be found in the SAREF4ENER extension, where classes such as PowerMax, PowerMin and PowerExpected are defined.

name: Pressure
comments: A saref:Property related to some measurements that are characterized by a certain value that is measured in a pressure unit (bar or pascal).

name: Price
comments: A saref:Property crelated to some measurements that are characterized by a certain value that is measured using saref:Currency.

name: Smoke
comments: A saref:Property related to some measurements that are characterized by a certain value that is measured in a unit of measure for smoke.

name: State of charge
comments: A property related to measurements of the battery status of a device. Measured in %. 100 % means fully charged. 0 % no charge.

name: Time
comments: A saref:Property that allows to specify the time concept in terms of instants or intervals according to the imported W3C Time ontology.

name: Voltage
comments: Voltage in Volts

name: Volume
comments: A property related to measurements measured in volume. Volume is measured in m³.

name: Service
comments: A service is a representation of a function to a network that makes the function discoverable, registerable, remotely controllable by other devices in the network. A service can represent one or more functions. A Service is offered by a device that wants (a certain set of) its function(s) to be discoverable, registerable, remotely controllable by other devices in the network. A Service must specify the device that is offering the service and the function(s) to be represented.

name: Switch on service
comments: A type of service that represents an on/off function to the network.

name: State
comments: The state in which a device can be found, e.g, ON/OFF/STANDBY, or ONLINE/OFFLINE. We propose here a list of states that are relevant for the purpose of SAREF, but this list can be extended.

name: Multi level state
comments: A type of state.

name: On off state
comments: A type of state.

name: On state
comments: A type of state.

name: On state
comments: A type of state.

name: Open close state
comments: A type of state.

name: Open state
comments: A type of state.

name: Close state
comments: A type of state.

name: Start stop state
comments: A type of state.

name: Start state
comments: A type of state.

name: Stop state
comments: A type of state.

name: Task
comments: The goal for which a device is designed (from a user perspective). For example, a washing machine is designed for the task of washing. We propose here a list of tasks that are relevant for the purpose of SAREF, but this list can be extended.

name: Temporal reference system
comments: A temporal reference system, such as a temporal coordinate system (with an origin, direction, and scale), a calendar-clock combination, or a (possibly hierarchical) ordinal system. This is a stub class, representing the set of all temporal reference systems.

name: Temporal duration
comments: Time extent; duration of a time interval separate from its particular start position.

name: Generalized duration description
comments: Description of temporal extent structured with separate values for the various elements of a calendar-clock system.

name: Duration description
comments: Description of temporal extent structured with separate values for the various elements of a calendar-clock system. The temporal reference system is fixed to Gregorian Calendar, and the range of each of the numeric properties is restricted to xsd:decimal

name: Year
comments: Year was proposed in the 2006 version of OWL-Time as an example of how DurationDescription could be specialized to allow for a duration to be restricted to a number of years.

name: Temporal unit
comments: Duration of a temporal extent expressed as a number scaled by a temporal unit

name: Time duration
comments: Duration of a temporal extent expressed as a number scaled by a temporal unit

name: Temporal entity
comments: A temporal interval or instant.

name: Time instant
comments: A temporal entity with zero extent or duration.

name: Time interval
comments: A temporal entity with an extent or duration.

name: Proper interval
comments: A temporal entity with non-zero extent or duration, i.e. for which the value of the beginning and end are different.

name: Date-time interval
comments: DateTimeInterval is a subclass of ProperInterval, defined using the multi-element DateTimeDescription.

name: Temporal position
comments: A position on a time-line

name: Generalized date-time description
comments: Some combinations of properties are redundant - for example, within a specified :year if :dayOfYear is provided then :day and :month can be computed, and vice versa. Individual values should be consistent with each other and the calendar, indicated through the value of the :hasTRS property.

name: Time position
comments: A temporal position described using either a (nominal) value from an ordinal reference system, or a (numeric) value in a temporal coordinate system.

name: Date-time description
comments: Description of date and time structured with separate values for the various elements of a calendar-clock system. The temporal reference system is fixed to Gregorian Calendar, and the range of year, month, day properties restricted to corresponding XML Schema types xsd:gYear, xsd:gMonth and xsd:gDay, respectively.

name: January
comments: This class was present in the 2006 version of OWL-Time. It was presented as an example of how DateTimeDescription could be specialized, but does not belong in the revised ontology.

name: Month of year
comments: The month of the year.

name: Time zone
comments: A Time Zone specifies the amount by which the local time is offset from UTC. A time zone is usually denoted geographically (e.g. Australian Eastern Daylight Time), with a constant value in a given region. The region where it applies and the offset from UTC are specified by a locally recognised governing authority.

name: Temporal position
comments: Position of a time instant.

name: Time position
comments: Position of an instant, expressed as a temporal coordinate or nominal value.
definitions: Position of a time instant expressed as a TimePosition

name: Time position
comments: Position of an instant, expressed as a temporal coordinate or nominal value.
definitions: Position of a time instant expressed as a TimePosition

name: in date-time description
comments: Position of an instant, expressed using a structured description.
definitions: Position of an instant, expressed using a structured description

name: Temporal reference system used
comments: The temporal reference system used by a temporal position or extent description.
definitions: The temporal reference system used by a temporal position or extent description.

name: accomplishes
comments: A relationship between a certain entity (e.g., a device) and the task it accomplishes.

name: acts upon
comments: A relationship between a command and a state.

name: after
comments: Gives directionality to time. If a temporal entity T1 is after another temporal entity T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.
definitions: Gives directionality to time. If a temporal entity T1 is after another temporal entity T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.

name: interval after
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalAfter another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalAfter another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.

name: before
comments: Gives directionality to time. If a temporal entity T1 is before another temporal entity T2, then the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2. Thus, 'before' can be considered to be basic to instants and derived for intervals.
definitions: Gives directionality to time. If a temporal entity T1 is before another temporal entity T2, then the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2. Thus, 'before' can be considered to be basic to instants and derived for intervals.

name: interval before
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalBefore another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalBefore another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2.

name: consists of
comments: A relationship indicating a composite entity that consists of other entities (e.g., a temperature/humidity sensor that consists of a temperature sensor and a humidity sensor)

name: controlled property
comments: A relationship specifying the Property that can be controlled by a certain Device.

name: day of week
comments: The day of week, whose value is a member of the class time:DayOfWeek.
definitions: The day of week, whose value is a member of the class time:DayOfWeek.

name: has date-time description
comments: Value of DateTimeInterval expressed as a structured value. The beginning and end of the interval coincide with the limits of the shortest element in the description.
definitions: Value of DateTimeInterval expressed as a structured value. The beginning and end of the interval coincide with the limits of the shortest element in the description.

name: has function
comments: A relationship identifying the type of function of a device.

name: has meter reading
comments: A relationship between a metering function and the measurement of the reading.

name: has meter reading type
comments: A relationship identifying the reading type of a measurement (e.g., Water, Gas, Pressure , Energy , Power, etc.).

name: has price
comments: A relationships indentifying the price associated to an entity.

name: has profile
comments: A relationship associating a profile to a certain entity (e.g., a device).

name: has room
comments: Things that have rooms...

name: has sensing range
comments: A relationship between a sensing function and a measurement identifying the range of a sensor detection.

name: has sensor type
comments: A relationship identifying the sensing type of a sensor detection (i.e., Temperature, Occupancy, Humidity, Motion , Smoke, Pressure, etc.)

name: has sensor state
comments: A relationship identifying the type of state of a device.

name: has duration description
comments: Duration of a temporal entity, expressed using a structured description.
definitions: Duration of a temporal entity, expressed using a structured description.

name: has threshold measurement
comments: A relationship associated with an event function to notify that a certain threshold measurement has been exceeded.

name: has time
comments: Supports the association of a temporal entity (instant or interval) to any thing

name: has beginning
comments: Beginning of a temporal entity.
definitions: Beginning of a temporal entity.

name: has end
comments: End of a temporal entity.
definitions: End of a temporal entity.

name: has time
comments: A relationship to associate time information to an entity.

name: has time instant inside
comments: An instant that falls inside the interval. It is not intended to include beginnings and ends of intervals.
definitions: An instant that falls inside the interval. It is not intended to include beginnings and ends of intervals.

name: has typical consumption
comments: A relationship identifying the typical (energy or power) consumption of a device.
definitions: A relationship identifying the typical (energy or power) consumption of a device.

name: in time zone
comments: The time zone for clock elements in the temporal position
skos_historyNotes: In the original 2006 version of OWL-Time, the range of time:timeZone was a TimeZone class in a separate namespace 'http://www.w3.org/2006/timezone#'. An alignment axiom tzont:TimeZone rdfs:subClassOf time:TimeZone . allows data encoded according to the previous version to be consistent with the updated ontology.
skos_notes: IANA maintains a database of timezones. These are well maintained and generally considered authoritative, but individual items are not available at individual URIs, so cannot be used directly in data expressed using OWL-Time. DBPedia provides a set of resources corresponding to the IANA timezones, with a URI for each (e.g. http://dbpedia.org/resource/Australia/Eucla). The World Clock service also provides a list of time zones with the description of each available as an individual webpage with a convenient individual URI (e.g. https://www.timeanddate.com/time/zones/acwst). These or other, similar, resources might be used as a value of the time:timeZone property.

name: interval contains
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalContains another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalContains another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.

name: interval contains
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalContains another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalContains another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.

name: interval disjoint
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalDisjoint another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2, or the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2, i.e. the intervals do not overlap in any way, but their ordering relationship is not known.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalDisjoint another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2, or the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2, i.e. the intervals do not overlap in any way, but their ordering relationship is not known.
skos_notes: This interval relation is not included in the 13 basic relationships defined in Allen (1984), but is defined in (T.3) as the union of :intervalBefore v :intervalAfter . However, that is outside OWL2 expressivity, so is implemented as an explicit property, with :intervalBefore , :intervalAfter as sub-properties.

name: interval after
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalAfter another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalAfter another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.

name: interval before
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalBefore another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalBefore another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2.

name: interval equals
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalEquals another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalEquals another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

name: interval finished by
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

name: interval in
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalIn another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2 or is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2, or is coincident with the end of T2, except that end of T1 may not be coincident with the end of T2 if the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalIn another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2 or is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2, or is coincident with the end of T2, except that end of T1 may not be coincident with the end of T2 if the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2.
skos_notes: This interval relation is not included in the 13 basic relationships defined in Allen (1984), but is referred to as 'an important relationship' in Allen and Ferguson (1997). It is the disjoint union of :intervalStarts v :intervalDuring v :intervalFinishes . However, that is outside OWL2 expressivity, so is implemented as an explicit property, with :intervalStarts , :intervalDuring , :intervalFinishes as sub-properties.

name: interval during
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalDuring another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalDuring another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

name: interval finishes
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishes another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishes another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

name: interval starts
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalStarts another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalStarts another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

name: interval meets
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalMeets another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalMeets another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2.

name: interval overlapped by
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalOverlappedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, the beginning of T1 is before the end of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalOverlappedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, the beginning of T1 is before the end of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.

name: interval overlaps
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalOverlaps another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, the end of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalOverlaps another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, the end of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

name: interval started by
comments: If a proper interval T1 is intervalStarted another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.
definitions: If a proper interval T1 is intervalStarted another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.

name: is about
comments: A relationship identifying what an entity, such as a Profile, is about.

name: is accomplished by
comments: A relationship indentifying the task accomplished by a certain entity (e.g., a device).

name: is command of
comments: A relationship between a command and a function.

name: is controlled by device
comments: A relationship specifying the devices that can control a certain property

name: is measured by device
comments: A relationship specifying the devices that can measure a certain property.

name: is measured in
comments: A relationship identifying the unit of measure used for a certain entity.

name: is offered in
comments: A relationship between a service and a device that offers the service.

name: is used for
comments: A relationship specifying the purpose for which a device is used for (e.g., controlling a Commodity).

name: makes measurement
comments: A relation between a device and the measurements it makes. Such measurement will link together the value of the measurement, its unit of measure and the property to which it relates.

name: measures property
comments: A relationship specifying the Property that can be measured by a certain Device.

name: month of year
comments: The month of the year, whose value is a member of the class time:MonthOfYear.
definitions: The month of the year, whose value is a member of the class time:MonthOfYear.
skos_notes: Feature at risk - added in 2017 revision, and not yet widely used.

name: offers
comments: A relationship between a device and a service.

name: relates to measurement
comments: A relationship between a property and the measurements it relates to.

name: relates to property
comments: A relationship between a measurement and the property it relates to.

name: represents
comments: A relationship between a service and a function.

name: temporal unit type
comments: The temporal unit which provides the precision of a date-time value or scale of a temporal extent

name: day
comments: Day position in a calendar-clock system. The range of this property is not specified, so can be replaced by any specific representation of a calendar day from any calendar.
definitions: Day position in a calendar-clock system. The range of this property is not specified, so can be replaced by any specific representation of a calendar day from any calendar.

name: day of year
comments: The number of the day within the year.
definitions: The number of the day within the year.

name: days duration
comments: Length of, or element of the length of, a temporal extent expressed in days.
definitions: :ength of, or element of the length of, a temporal extent expressed in days.

name: has XSD duration
definitions: Extent of a temporal entity, expressed using xsd:duration.
skos_notes: Feature at risk - added in 2017 revision, and not yet widely used. In range of: duration

name: has_description
comments: A relationship providing a description of an entity (e.g., device).

name: has manufacturer
comments: A relationship identifying the manufacturer of an entity (e.g., device). In range of xsd:string

name: hour
comments: Hour position in a calendar-clock system.
definitions: Hour position in a calendar-clock system.

name: hours duration
comments: length of, or element of the length of, a temporal extent expressed in hours.
definitions: length of, or element of the length of, a temporal extent expressed in hours.

comments: Position of an instant, expressed using xsd:dateTimeStamp.
definitions: Position of an instant, expressed using xsd:dateTimeStamp.

comments: Position of an instant, expressed using xsd:dateTimeStamp.

name: week
skos_notes: Weeks are numbered differently depending on the calendar in use and the local language or cultural conventions (locale). ISO-8601 specifies that the first week of the year includes at least four days, and that Monday is the first day of the week. In that system, week 1 is the week that contains the first Thursday in the year.
